{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"body":"FIELD FINDING (plan-review claim gate non-convergence) — captured while executing this epic under /rebar-implement, 2026-07-12. Attempting to earn plan-review attestations for the 10 child leaves reproduced, at scale, the exact pathology this epic targets:\n\n1. VERDICT INSTABILITY on identical plans: 74d9 and a8e5 each returned INDETERMINATE (0 blocking) on one round, then BLOCK (1 and 3 blocking respectively) on the very next round with the plan text UNCHANGED (only re-run). This is the >=32% same-material verdict instability from bug 5e40 (story a8e5's motivator), observed directly on the claim gate.\n\n2. NON-MONOTONIC / NON-CONVERGENT remediation: block counts oscillate rather than decrease as valid findings are remediated. b9c0: 7 -> 4 -> 4 -> 6 blocks across 4 rounds (each round I fixed the named findings). 74d9: 1 -> 6 -> 2 -> INDETERMINATE -> 1. 9f25: 4 -> 1 -> 3. Each remediation that adds specificity mints new finer-grained findings (the ~95%-of-edits-mint-new-findings effect the epic Context cites), and verdict noise moves the count both ways.\n\n3. NEW-CODE GROUNDING GAP: codebase-grounding criteria (G1G2/E4) abstain or return INDETERMINATE for plans that reference not-yet-written code (a new scorer, a new binary, a new field) — which is inherent to planning NEW work. This is structurally distinct from advisory churn and is a candidate for the a37b/a8e5 grounding hardening.\n\n4. EXHAUSTIVE-BLAST-RADIUS TAIL: for b9c0's config flip, the gate enumerated the breaking pinning tests ONE per round (test_impact_model_versioning -> test_code_review_ws2:64 -> ws2:39/52 -> ...), rather than all at once, forcing a round per discovered test.\n\nAll blocks encountered were, individually, VALID and sharp (real spec gaps, false premises, missing edit targets, tautological tests, schema mismatches) — the gate's precision is good. The problem is CONVERGENCE + STABILITY at the aggregate/claim level: a fail-closed gate that does not monotonically converge cannot be satisfied by honest iterative remediation within a bounded number of rounds, especially for complex, dependency-coupled leaves (b9c0's correct threshold genuinely depends on sibling 9f25's not-yet-performed derivation). This is direct evidence for the epic's Success Criteria (code-review looseness is one half; plan-review over-tightness/instability is the mirror) and belongs in the epic's measurement note."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1783893622250753001,"uuid":"72bd30af-3775-42a0-a276-c912ccc6d30c"}